issue(id="XXXX" status="open")
  title Codify safety principles for redteam.js as a defensive, reviewable auditor
  user-story
    as-a redteam.js maintainer preparing a reusable adversarial auditor
    i-want an explicit safety-principles document for the project
    so-that we keep the software effective for authorized security validation without turning it into an unsafe or misleading npm package
  premise.
    redteam.js should simulate realistic attacker behavior, but it should not
    inherit the consent model or distribution posture of malware. The project
    needs a short principles document that makes that distinction explicit for
    maintainers, contributors, reviewers, and downstream users.

    The core idea is: realistic attacker behavior, unrealistic consent model.
    The harness should emulate the kinds of reads, pivots, and exfiltration
    attempts that package-borne malware would try, while remaining obviously
    opt-in, reviewable, controlled, and defensive in operation.

    This is especially important if any part of the work ever resembles a
    public npm package. We want to be good ecosystem citizens: no surprise
    lifecycle hooks, no hidden network behavior, no turnkey secret theft, and
    no ambiguity about the fact that the tool is for authorized validation.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion redteam.js has a short principles document or equivalent top-level design note that explains the project's safety posture in plain language.
    criterion The document states that redteam.js is opt-in and intentional, and that installation alone must not trigger probes, stealthy behavior, or surprise network activity.
    criterion The document states that dangerous capabilities should be inert by default, with stronger read, persistence, and exfiltration behavior gated behind explicit operator choice.
    criterion The document prefers proof of reachability over collection of sensitive contents by default, and it explains when deeper validation may be justified under explicit authorization.
    criterion The document commits to controlled endpoints, local sinks, clear labeling, guardrails, and easy cleanup rather than malware-like collection or third-party exfiltration.
    criterion The document records a packaging stance that keeps anything too weapon-like out of a casual public npm consumption path, favoring obviously defensive distribution and documentation.
  review-items
    item(status="open").
      Include the high-level principle `realistic attacker behavior,
      unrealistic consent model` near the top of the document so the project
      has a clear north star for future design decisions.
    item(status="open").
      State that the safe baseline is explicit operator intent: no install-time
      execution, no hidden lifecycle scripts, no stealth, and no probes that
      quietly begin on package install or ordinary import.
    item(status="open").
      Describe the default operating model as inert-by-default. File reads,
      persistence checks, outbound exfil tests, and similar sensitive probe
      families should require explicit flags, target configuration, or a
      purpose-built harness rather than turning on implicitly.
    item(status="open").
      Prefer reporting reachability over collecting secrets. For example, it is
      usually enough to record that a path existed and was readable, or that a
      process environment contained interesting variable names, without copying
      the secret material itself unless the operator deliberately authorizes a
      deeper validation mode.
    item(status="open").
      Require controlled destinations for exfiltration simulation. Use local
      sinks, controlled test endpoints, or dry-run/report-only paths, and do
      not ever send findings to unrelated third-party infrastructure.
    item(status="open").
      Document guardrails such as target allowlists, path scopes, redaction,
      rate limits, max file sizes, and hard stops around especially sensitive
      locations unless the operator has explicitly expanded scope.
    item(status="open").
      Make transparency part of the safety story: clear docs, clear runtime
      output, and report labels such as `simulated exfil`, `readability
      confirmed`, `not attempted`, and `not applicable`.
    item(status="open").
      Keep cleanup first-class. Temporary fixtures, listeners, tokens, and
      generated artifacts should be ephemeral and easy to remove so the tool
      does not leave confusing or risky residue behind.
    item(status="open").
      Capture an architectural preference for a safe orchestration core plus
      explicit probe modules. That split should help reviewers understand which
      parts are policy and reporting versus which parts simulate attacker
      actions.
    item(status="open").
      Note the packaging and distribution posture explicitly. If a feature set
      starts to resemble a turnkey abuse kit, it likely belongs in a private
      registry, internal repository, or tightly scoped operator workflow
      instead of broad public npm distribution.
    item(status="open").
      Mention the specific bias for `scrubs`: default to proving what dirty
      space can reach rather than normalizing the collection of real secrets.
